\subsection{draft: Principal Component Regression}
\begin{frame}[fragile,t]{\subsecname}
\vspace{-1em}
\begin{block}{}
  \begin{columns}[T]
    \column{0.5\textwidth}
      In \emph{Principal Component Regression} (\emph{PCR}), the \emph{design matrix} $\mathbb{X}$ is mulltiplied by a \emph{PCA rotation matrix} $\mathbb{W}$:
      \begin{displaymath}
        \mathbb{X}_{pca} = \mathbb{X} \mathbb{W}
      \end{displaymath}
      The matrix $\mathbb{W}$ is chosen so that the columns (principal components) of the \emph{PCA design matrix} $\mathbb{X}_{pca}$ form an orthogonal set of predictors.
      \vskip1ex
      The \emph{PCA design matrix} $\mathbb{X}_{pca}$ produces the same \emph{influence matrix} $\mathbb{H}$ as the original \emph{design matrix} $\mathbb{X}$, so \emph{Principal Component Regression} is equivalent to the original regression model.
      \vskip1ex
      \emph{Principal Component Regression} is used to:
      \begin{itemize}
        \item Remove \emph{collinearity} between predictors, by excluding principal components with very small eignevalues,
        \item Perform \emph{dimension reduction}, by including only principal components with significantly large eignevalues,
        \item Reduce model overfitting, by reducing the number of predictors and parameters.
      \end{itemize}
    \column{0.5\textwidth}
      \vspace{-1em}
        <<echo=TRUE,eval=TRUE>>=
# Perform PCA
pcad <- prcomp(design, center=FALSE, scale=FALSE)
design_pcr <- pcad$x
# Principal components are orthogonal to each other
round(t(design_pcr) %*% design_pcr, 2)
round(apply(design_pcr, 2,
  function(x) c(mean=mean(x), sd=sd(x))), 3)
# Calculate the PCR influence matrix
influence_pcr <- design_pcr %*% MASS::ginv(design_pcr)
all.equal(influ_ence, influence_pcr)
      @
  \end{columns}
\end{block}

\end{frame}


